{"title":"Col de Peyresoude: A Tour de France institution","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-de-peyresoude","date":1696246747000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-de-peyresoude\">Col de Peyresoude: A Tour de France institution</a></p>\n\n<p>Think of the Tour de France and you invariably think of mountains, and it was on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-history-lapize-tames-the-pyrenees\" target=\"_blank\">Stage 10 of the 1910 Tour</a> that the riders went above 1,500m for the first time. The setting for this milestone was the Col de Peyresourde, 1,595m above sea level and the gateway to the <em>Grand Boucle</em>’s first foray into the high mountains – and what a foray it was. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The Peyresourde led onto the Col d’Aspin, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/classic-tour-de-france-climbs-col-du-tourmalet\" target=\"_blank\">Col du Tourmalet</a>, Col du Soulor and <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-d-aubisque-tour-de-france\" target=\"_blank\">Col d’Aubisque</a> to make for a 326km-long stage with some 6,500m of climbing.</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/best-cycling-french-pyrenees\">Best places to cycle in the French Pyrenees</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/classic-tour-de-france-climbs-col-du-tourmalet\">Classic Tour de France climbs: Col du Tourmalet</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/cyclist-magazine-new-issue-on-sale-buy-it-now\">Cyclist magazine issue 144: on sale now!</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<p>Bagnères-de-Luchon hosted the <em>départ</em>, meaning there wasn’t so much as half a kilometre for the riders to warm up before they hit the first slopes of the Peyresourde. Little surprise, then, that eventual winner Octave Lapize took a staggering 14 hours and ten minutes to reach the finish line in Bayonne. Pushing his bike up the rough tracks of the Ausbisque, the Frenchman would utter the immortal words, ‘<em>Vous êtes des assassins!</em>’ – ‘you are assassins’.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-02.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>Reminders of the frequent visits by the Tour de France, and thousands of fans, are everywhere.</figcaption><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>History was made, the assassins having changed the complexion of the Tour forever, yet it’s curious to think it almost didn’t happen. Race organiser Henri Desgrange was allegedly anxious such mountains would turn his spectacle into a farce, and it was only the petitioning by <em>L’Auto</em> journalist Alphonse Steinès that got the race here at all. In the years since, one might argue the Tourmalet has become the bigger star, but there’s a reason the Tour has returned to the Peyresourde 71 times and counting.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Great expectations</h2>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"647\" height=\"970\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-03-647x970.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-03-647x970.jpg 647w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-03-200x300.jpg 200w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-03-768x1151.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-03-1025x1536.jpg 1025w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-03-750x1124.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-03-1140x1709.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-03.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Given its fame and legacy, anticipation for the Peyresourde runs high, but this is a climb that more than lives up to its billing. It gets pretty almost straight out of Bagnères-de-Luchon, and within the first kilometre you can look back over your shoulder at the town, at the Superbagnères ski station towering above it and a vivid green forest in your wake.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>From here the Peyresourde doles out its spectacular scenes in distinct chapters.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-04.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>The first, some 5km long, sees a stone wall a near-constant companion, a bodyguard holding back the mountain from crushing you, the road weaving steadily save for a set of three punctuating switchbacks. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The second chapter has a backdrop whose beauty seems disproportionate to the modest altitude gained; the third includes the junction with the D51, better known as the 1,755m Port de Balès.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-05.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The two iconic, stone-walled switchbacks in the final kilometre are like balconies with huge views back across the valley.</figcaption><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>What follows is a tough section at 10%, once more walled in as it delivers you towards a pair of picturesque villages, each adorned with painted bikes in tribute to the Tour. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>On to the villages of Saint-Aventin and Garin and the valley opens out to your left, and yet the col is still not visible. Off to one side, but worthy of mention, is the village of Oô, which is pronounced ‘<em>ooh’</em> – an apposite word for this area.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-06.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>The valley splits, and upon leaving Garin you find yourself looking out to the right, towards an all-new mountain-scape slowly making itself known through the trees. It’s here that this chapter closes and another opens, as the Peyresourde’s summit finally comes into view – a sight indicating that just over 3km remains.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The deep saddle of the ridgeline is silhouetted against the sky, a lone tree atop it. Just below, pinned to a steep face, the Peyresourde’s two iconic, walled switchbacks glint stonily.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/subscriptions\"><img width=\"970\" height=\"347\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/clickable-subs-promo4-970x347.jpg\" alt=\"Subscribe to Cyclist Magazine\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/clickable-subs-promo4-970x347.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/clickable-subs-promo4-300x107.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/clickable-subs-promo4-768x275.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/clickable-subs-promo4-1536x550.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/clickable-subs-promo4-750x269.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/clickable-subs-promo4-1140x408.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/clickable-subs-promo4.jpg 1818w\" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>It’s here that Tadej Pogačar attacked on Stage 8 of the 2020 Tour, going solo over the top then propelling himself down to the finish in Loudenvielle and back into GC contention. His first yellow jersey win would come soon after. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>As you climb this same road it’s sobering to think Pogačar dispensed with the whole of the Peyresourde in just 24min 35sec, a record. But that’s easy when you’re putting out 6.7 watts/kg.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"647\" height=\"970\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-07-647x970.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-07-647x970.jpg 647w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-07-200x300.jpg 200w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-07-768x1151.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-07-1025x1536.jpg 1025w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-07-750x1124.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-07-1140x1709.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-07.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The last ramp to the summit is the time to dig deep into your suitcase of courage.</figcaption><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Those stone-walled switchbacks are as epic to ride as they are to see from a distance, but happily there’s a generous amount of zig before you zag, so the gradient remains manageable. At the first switchback you can look up to see the second; by the second you feel perched in the air as if viewing the world from a skyscraper. </p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Always the bridesmaid</h2>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-08.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The final two switchbacks are the Peyresourde’s signature and provide a handy countdown to the summit.</figcaption><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>The summit itself is fantastic, cinema in real time. The road is dead straight over the top so you’re treated to a real sense of reaching a crest. A stunning reveal of the peaks unfolds in the distance, then to top it off – some great reward – there’s a little cafe serving crêpes by the stack. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>It’s a perfect place to stop, to refuel and drink in the view: the Col de Val Louron-Azet layered over the top of a massive line of mountains that includes the 2,215m Col de Portet.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-09.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The road runs dead straight over the crest at the 1,569m summit, delivering a sublime reveal of the view ahead.</figcaption><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Incredibly, the Col de Peyresourde has never been a summit finish, but that’s because its real value to the Tour – just as in 1910 – is as a mid-stage pass to visit other mountains. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The nearest the Peyresourde ever gets is with a finish at the adjacent Peyragudes ski station and its viciously steep altiport runway, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-2022-stage-17-gallery-pogacar\" target=\"_blank\">a combination used in 2022</a> when Jonas Vingegaard lost Stage 17’s battle with Pogačar but went on to win the war. 2017 was another stellar year, when <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/romain-bardet-wins-tour-de-france-stage-12-aru-takes-yellow\">Romain Bardet won</a> and Fabio Aru delayed the yellow jersey from reaching its inevitable final destination on the shoulders of Chris Froome.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Classic Climb Peyresourde\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/classic-climb-peyresourde-10.jpg 1200w\" /><figcaption>The rider’s eye view of the summit and the ranges beyond.</figcaption><figcaption>Alex Duffill / Cyclist</figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>The Peyresourde has also been significant as a descent for a finish in Bagnères-de-Luchon. Exactly 40 years ago, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/pippa-york\" target=\"_blank\">Philippa York</a> (then known as Robert Millar) attacked over the top and super-tucked the descent to take a breakthrough win, both for her and for British cycling. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>There had been British stage winners before, including in the mountains, but not from the GC group, and never like that. Watching at home that day was a young, highly impressionable Bradley Wiggins. The Peyresourde, sometimes quietly, at other times more brashly, has been shaping the Tour de France for over a hundred years.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>• This article originally appeared in issue 144 of <em>Cyclist </em>magazine. <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/subscriptions\" target=\"_blank\">Click here to subscribe</a></strong></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-de-peyresoude\">Col de Peyresoude: A Tour de France institution</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"mdonlevy","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"dc6f5a884e2e2a3b46c276d2e090e6cfb2eff42d53aa0a3791debd6d260e60ca","category":"Cycling"}